THOUGHT: The miscompile happens because InstCombine alters the fcmp predicate around zero under NSZ, and that change propagates into a select that returns a specific signed zero, causing observable differences (+0.0 vs -0.0). A safe, conservative fix is to prevent predicate-altering folds on an FCmp when it directly feeds a Select that has a floating-point zero literal on one of its arms. This avoids the problematic rewrite in such sensitive contexts while keeping other optimizations intact. I will modify visitFCmpInst to early-exit (do no further folding) if the fcmp has a single select user and either select arm is any FP zero.

```bash
applypatch << 'EOF'
*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp
@@
   8555	  // operands has at least one user besides the compare (the select),
   8556	  // which would often largely negate the benefit of folding anyway.
   8557	  if (I.hasOneUse())
   8558	    if (SelectInst *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(I.user_back())) {
   8559	      Value *A, *B;
   8560	      SelectPatternResult SPR = matchSelectPattern(SI, A, B);
   8561	      if (SPR.Flavor != SPF_UNKNOWN)
   8562	        return nullptr;
+ 8563	      // Additionally, avoid folding the compare if the select arms include a
+ 8564	      // floating-point zero literal. Changing the compare predicate around zero
+ 8565	      // (e.g., olt -> ole) under NSZ can alter which arm is chosen and expose
+ 8566	      // a specific signed-zero (-0.0) which is observable in the select result.
+ 8567	      // To preserve the original semantics in such sensitive cases, bail out.
+ 8568	      auto IsAnyZeroFP = [](Value *V) {
+ 8569	        return match(V, m_AnyZeroFP());
+ 8570	      };
+ 8571	      if (IsAnyZeroFP(SI->getTrueValue()) || IsAnyZeroFP(SI->getFalseValue()))
+ 8572	        return nullptr;
   8563	    }
*** End Patch
EOF
```

